Note:
This file handles data flow analysis and variable tracking.

This file performs the following tasks:
- Process data flow analysis and variable tracking
- Handle data flow graph construction and data flow graph analysis
- Manage data flow optimization and data flow optimization
- Process data flow validation and data flow validation

This file is essential because of the following reasons:
- Data flow analysis enables variable tracking and optimization opportunities
- Proper data flow handling ensures correct variable flow tracking
- Data flow analysis support enables Runa compilation for data-aware code generation

This file consists of the following functions/features/operation types:
- Data flow analysis and variable tracking (Kildall's framework)
- Reaching definitions analysis (forward data flow)
- Live variables analysis (backward data flow)
- Def-use chain construction (MIR SSA-aware, LIR register-based)
- Liveness computation for register allocation

Dependencies:
- compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa (MIR structures, SSA values, canonical accessors)
- compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir_nodes.runa (call/phi extended-record accessors)
- compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/cfg.runa (CFG accessors, instruction use extraction)
- compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa (LIR structures, virtual registers)
- compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/liveness.runa (canonical ABI-correct LIR liveness)
- compiler/middle/analysis/control_flow.runa (CFG structures)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa (OWNED HEAP allocation - Tier 3)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa (instruction tracking)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/ordered_map.runa (integer-keyed value/block maps)
- compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/set.runa (liveness sets)
- compiler/internal/string_utils.runa (integer-to-string for diagnostics)
:End Note

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir.runa" as MIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/mir_nodes.runa" as MIRNodes
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/mir/cfg.runa" as MirCFG
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/lir.runa" as LIR
Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/liveness.runa" as LIRLiveness
Import "compiler/middle/analysis/control_flow.runa" as CFG
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/ordered_map.runa" as OrderedMap
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/set.runa" as Set
Import "compiler/internal/string_utils.runa" as StringUtils

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DATA FLOW ANALYSIS TYPE DEFINITIONS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
LivenessInfo stores the live variable analysis results for a single basic block.

Fields:
- block_id: The basic block ID this liveness info belongs to
- live_in: Set of variables live on entry to the block
- live_out: Set of variables live on exit from the block
- gen: Set of variables generated (defined) in the block before any use
- kill: Set of variables killed (defined) in the block
- uses: Set of variables used in the block before any definition
- defs: Set of variables defined in the block

Liveness equations (backward data flow):
  live_in[B] = uses[B] ∪ (live_out[B] - defs[B])
  live_out[B] = ∪_{S ∈ successors[B]} live_in[S]

Memory: Tier 3 (OWNED HEAP)
Size: 8 fields × 8 bytes = 64 bytes
@End Reasoning

Type called "LivenessInfo":
    block_id as Integer         Note: Basic block ID
    live_in as Integer          Note: Set of live-in variables
    live_out as Integer         Note: Set of live-out variables
    gen as Integer              Note: Set of generated variables
    kill as Integer             Note: Set of killed variables
    uses as Integer             Note: Set of used variables
    defs as Integer             Note: Set of defined variables
    iteration_count as Integer  Note: Number of fixed-point iterations (debugging)
End Type

Note: Field offsets: 0, 8, 16, 24, 32, 40, 48, 56

@Reasoning
ReachingDefInfo stores reaching definitions analysis results for a single block.

Reaching definitions identify which definitions of a variable can reach a
given program point. This is a forward data flow problem.

Fields:
- block_id: The basic block ID
- reach_in: Set of definition IDs reaching the block entry
- reach_out: Set of definition IDs reaching the block exit
- gen: Set of definitions generated in this block
- kill: Set of definitions killed in this block

Reaching definitions equations (forward data flow):
  reach_out[B] = gen[B] ∪ (reach_in[B] - kill[B])
  reach_in[B] = ∪_{P ∈ predecessors[B]} reach_out[P]

Memory: Tier 3 (OWNED HEAP)
Size: 5 fields × 8 bytes = 40 bytes
@End Reasoning

Type called "ReachingDefInfo":
    block_id as Integer         Note: Basic block ID
    reach_in as Integer         Note: Set of reaching definition IDs
    reach_out as Integer        Note: Set of reaching definition IDs
    gen as Integer              Note: Set of generated definition IDs
    kill as Integer             Note: Set of killed definition IDs
End Type

Note: Field offsets: 0, 8, 16, 24, 32

@Reasoning
DefUseChain represents the definition-use relationship for a single value.

For MIR (SSA form):
- Each SSA value has exactly one definition (def_instruction)
- But can have multiple uses (use_list)

For LIR (non-SSA):
- Each virtual register can have multiple definitions
- Each definition can have multiple uses
- Chains are more complex than SSA

Fields:
- def_id: Definition ID (instruction pointer or SSA value ID)
- use_ids: List of use IDs (instruction pointers or value IDs)
- def_block_id: Block where definition occurs
- use_block_ids: List of blocks where uses occur

Memory: Tier 3 (OWNED HEAP)
Size: 4 fields × 8 bytes = 32 bytes
@End Reasoning

Type called "DefUseChain":
    def_id as Integer           Note: Definition ID (instruction or value)
    use_ids as Integer          Note: List of use IDs
    def_block_id as Integer     Note: Block ID of definition
    use_block_ids as Integer    Note: List of block IDs for uses
End Type

Note: Field offsets: 0, 8, 16, 24

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DATA FLOW STRUCTURE INITIALIZATION
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Creates a LivenessInfo structure for a single basic block.
Initializes all sets to empty and prepares for liveness analysis.

Memory: Tier 3 (OWNED HEAP) - 64 bytes
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_liveness_info" that takes block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate LivenessInfo structure (64 bytes)
    Let liveness be proc allocate from Layout with 64
    If liveness is equal to 0:
        Display "create_liveness_info: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set block_id (offset 0)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with liveness, 0, block_id

    Note: Create empty sets for liveness tracking
    Let live_in be proc create from Set
    Let live_out be proc create from Set
    Let gen be proc create from Set
    Let kill be proc create from Set
    Let uses be proc create from Set
    Let defs be proc create from Set

    Note: Store sets in structure
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with liveness, 8, live_in Note: live_in
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with liveness, 16, live_out Note: live_out
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with liveness, 24, gen Note: gen
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with liveness, 32, kill Note: kill
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with liveness, 40, uses Note: uses
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with liveness, 48, defs Note: defs

    Note: Initialize iteration count to 0
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with liveness, 56, 0

    Return liveness
End Process

@Reasoning
Creates a ReachingDefInfo structure for a single basic block.
Initializes all sets to empty for reaching definitions analysis.

Memory: Tier 3 (OWNED HEAP) - 40 bytes
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_reaching_def_info" that takes block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate ReachingDefInfo structure (40 bytes)
    Let reach_info be proc allocate from Layout with 40
    If reach_info is equal to 0:
        Display "create_reaching_def_info: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set block_id (offset 0)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 0, block_id

    Note: Create empty sets for reaching definitions tracking
    Let reach_in be proc create from Set
    Let reach_out be proc create from Set
    Let gen be proc create from Set
    Let kill be proc create from Set

    Note: Store sets in structure
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 8, reach_in Note: reach_in
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 16, reach_out Note: reach_out
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 24, gen Note: gen
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 32, kill Note: kill

    Return reach_info
End Process

@Reasoning
Creates a DefUseChain structure linking a definition to its uses.

Memory: Tier 3 (OWNED HEAP) - 32 bytes
@End Reasoning

Process called "create_def_use_chain" that takes def_id as Integer, def_block_id as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Allocate DefUseChain structure (32 bytes)
    Let chain be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    If chain is equal to 0:
        Display "create_def_use_chain: allocation failed"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Set def_id (offset 0)
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with chain, 0, def_id

    Note: Create empty lists for uses
    Let use_ids be proc create from List
    Let use_block_ids be proc create from List

    Note: Store in structure
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with chain, 8, use_ids Note: use_ids
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with chain, 16, def_block_id Note: def_block_id
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with chain, 24, use_block_ids Note: use_block_ids

    Return chain
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: REACHING DEFINITIONS ANALYSIS (Forward Data Flow)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Computes reaching definitions for all blocks in the CFG using Kildall's
monotone data flow framework (forward analysis).

Algorithm:
1. Initialize: reach_in[entry] = ∅, reach_in[B] = ∅ for all other blocks
2. Compute gen/kill sets for each block:
   - gen[B] = definitions generated in B
   - kill[B] = definitions killed by B
3. Fixed-point iteration:
   - reach_in[B] = ∪_{P ∈ pred[B]} reach_out[P]
   - reach_out[B] = gen[B] ∪ (reach_in[B] - kill[B])
4. Iterate until no changes (fixed point)

Complexity: O(N * D * I) where N = blocks, D = definitions, I = iterations
Typical iterations: 2-5 for most programs

Returns: Dictionary mapping block_id -> ReachingDefInfo
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_reaching_definitions_mir" that takes mir_cfg as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_cfg is equal to 0:
        Display "compute_reaching_definitions_mir: null CFG"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Canonical MIRCFG: blocks List at offset 16, entry_block at offset 0.
    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from MirCFG with mir_cfg
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Display "compute_reaching_definitions_mir: null blocks list"
        Return 0
    End If
    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks
    Let entry_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_cfg, 0
    Let entry_id be 0
    If entry_block is not equal to 0:
        Set entry_id to proc get_mir_basic_block_id from MirCFG with entry_block
    End If

    If block_count is equal to 0:
        Display "compute_reaching_definitions_mir: empty CFG"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create reaching definition info for each block, keyed on the
    Note: integer block_id through an ordered_map (collections/dictionary
    Note: string-hashes its keys, which segfaults on integer keys).
    Let reach_infos be proc omap_create from OrderedMap

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let block_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from MirCFG with block

        Let reach_info be create_reaching_def_info(block_id)
        proc omap_set from OrderedMap with reach_infos, block_id, reach_info

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Note: Compute gen/kill sets for each block. A reaching definition is
    Note: identified by the DEFINING INSTRUCTION pointer; gen[B] is the set
    Note: of instructions in B that produce an SSA value (value_id != 0).
    Note: In SSA every value is defined exactly once, so a block never
    Note: redefines a value defined elsewhere — kill[B] is empty by SSA's
    Note: single-assignment invariant (phi nodes merge, they do not kill).
    Set b to 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Set block to proc get from List with blocks, b
        Set block_id to proc get_mir_basic_block_id from MirCFG with block
        Set reach_info to proc omap_get from OrderedMap with reach_infos, block_id

        Let gen_set be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 24

        Note: Canonical block: instruction List at offset 16, count at offset 24.
        Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block
        Let inst_count be proc get_block_instruction_count from MIR with block

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i

            Note: Canonical: SSA result value-id lives in the MIRNode header
            Note: value_id slot (offset 8); 0 means non-producing.
            Let value_id be proc get_mir_node_value_id from MIR with inst
            If value_id is not equal to 0:
                proc add from Set with gen_set, inst
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Note: Fixed-point iteration for reach_in/reach_out (forward dataflow)
    Let changed be 1
    Let iteration be 0

    While changed is equal to 1:
        If iteration is greater than or equal to 100:
            Set changed to 0
        Otherwise:
                Set changed to 0
                Set iteration to iteration plus 1

                Note: For each block (except entry, whose reach_in is empty)
                Set b to 0
                While b is less than block_count:
                    Set block to proc get from List with blocks, b
                    Set block_id to proc get_mir_basic_block_id from MirCFG with block

                    Note: Skip entry block (reach_in[entry] = empty)
                    If block_id is equal to entry_id:
                        Set b to b plus 1
                        Continue
                    End If

                    Set reach_info to proc omap_get from OrderedMap with reach_infos, block_id
                    Let reach_in be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 8
                    Let reach_out be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 16
                    Let gen be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 24
                    Let kill be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 32

                    Note: Compute new reach_in = ∪_{P ∈ pred[B]} reach_out[P].
                    Note: Predecessors are a List of block IDS (canonical
                    Note: MIRBasicBlock offset 32); resolve each id to its
                    Note: block then to its reach_info entry.
                    Let new_reach_in be proc create from Set

                    Let predecessors be proc get_block_predecessors from MIR with block
                    Let pred_count be proc get_block_predecessor_count from MIR with block

                    Let p be 0
                    While p is less than pred_count:
                        Let pred_id be proc get from List with predecessors, p
                        Let pred_reach_info be proc omap_get from OrderedMap with reach_infos, pred_id
                        If pred_reach_info is not equal to 0:
                            Let pred_reach_out be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with pred_reach_info, 16

                            Note: Union with predecessor's reach_out
                            Let pred_reach_out_list be proc to_list from Set with pred_reach_out
                            Let pred_size be proc length from List with pred_reach_out_list
                            Let j be 0
                            While j is less than pred_size:
                                Let def_id be proc get from List with pred_reach_out_list, j
                                proc add from Set with new_reach_in, def_id
                                Set j to j plus 1
                            End While
                        End If

                        Set p to p plus 1
                    End While

                    Note: Check if reach_in changed
                    Let old_size be proc size from Set with reach_in
                    Let new_size be proc size from Set with new_reach_in
                    If old_size is not equal to new_size:
                        Set changed to 1
                    End If

                    Note: Update reach_in (replacing the prior set)
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 8, new_reach_in

                    Note: Compute reach_out = gen ∪ (reach_in - kill)
                    Let new_reach_out be proc create from Set

                    Note: Add gen set
                    Let gen_list be proc to_list from Set with gen
                    Let gen_size be proc length from List with gen_list
                    Set j to 0
                    While j is less than gen_size:
                        Set def_id to proc get from List with gen_list, j
                        proc add from Set with new_reach_out, def_id
                        Set j to j plus 1
                    End While

                    Note: Add (reach_in - kill)
                    Let reach_in_list be proc to_list from Set with new_reach_in
                    Let reach_in_size be proc length from List with reach_in_list
                    Set j to 0
                    While j is less than reach_in_size:
                        Set def_id to proc get from List with reach_in_list, j
                        If proc contains from Set with kill, def_id is equal to 0:
                            proc add from Set with new_reach_out, def_id
                        End If
                        Set j to j plus 1
                    End While

                    Note: Check if reach_out changed
                    Let old_out_size be proc size from Set with reach_out
                    Let new_out_size be proc size from Set with new_reach_out
                    If old_out_size is not equal to new_out_size:
                        Set changed to 1
                    End If

                    Note: Update reach_out
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 16, new_reach_out

                    Set b to b plus 1
                End While
        End If
    End While

    Note: Fixed-point reached or max iterations
    If iteration is greater than or equal to 100:
        Display "compute_reaching_definitions_mir: max iterations reached"
    End If

    Return reach_infos
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIVE VARIABLES ANALYSIS (Backward Data Flow - Kildall's Framework)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Computes live variable analysis for all blocks in the CFG using Kildall's
monotone data flow framework (backward analysis).

A variable is "live" at a program point if its value may be used before
being redefined. This is crucial for register allocation.

Algorithm:
1. Initialize: live_out[exit] = ∅, live_out[B] = ∅ for all other blocks
2. Compute uses/defs sets for each block:
   - uses[B] = variables used before any definition in B
   - defs[B] = variables defined in B
3. Fixed-point iteration (backward):
   - live_out[B] = ∪_{S ∈ succ[B]} live_in[S]
   - live_in[B] = uses[B] ∪ (live_out[B] - defs[B])
4. Iterate until no changes (fixed point)

Complexity: O(N * V * I) where N = blocks, V = variables, I = iterations
Typical iterations: 2-5 for most programs

Returns: Dictionary mapping block_id -> LivenessInfo
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_live_variables_mir" that takes mir_cfg as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_cfg is equal to 0:
        Display "compute_live_variables_mir: null CFG"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Canonical MIRCFG: blocks List at offset 16.
    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from MirCFG with mir_cfg
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Display "compute_live_variables_mir: null blocks list"
        Return 0
    End If
    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks

    If block_count is equal to 0:
        Display "compute_live_variables_mir: empty CFG"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Create liveness info for each block, keyed on the integer block_id
    Note: through an ordered_map (collections/dictionary string-hashes its
    Note: keys, which segfaults on integer keys — the Wave 3 crash class).
    Let liveness_infos be proc omap_create from OrderedMap

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let block_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from MirCFG with block

        Let liveness be create_liveness_info(block_id)
        proc omap_set from OrderedMap with liveness_infos, block_id, liveness

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Note: Compute uses/defs sets for each block.
    Note: USE[B]  = value-ids read before any definition in B.
    Note: DEF[B]  = value-ids written in B.
    Note: Uses are extracted canonically: CFG.get_instruction_used_values
    Note: enumerates header operand slots and PHI incoming values as raw
    Note: SSA value-ids; call/invoke argument Lists carry additional uses
    Note: at the prefix-embedded args slot, which that enumerator omits, so
    Note: they are folded in here. The definition is the MIRNode header
    Note: value_id (offset 8), 0 for non-producing instructions.
    Set b to 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Set block to proc get from List with blocks, b
        Set block_id to proc get_mir_basic_block_id from MirCFG with block
        Set liveness to proc omap_get from OrderedMap with liveness_infos, block_id

        Let uses be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 40
        Let defs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 48

        Note: Track which variables are defined so far in this block (a
        Note: later use of a locally-defined value is NOT a block-level use).
        Let defined_in_block be proc create from Set

        Note: Canonical block: instruction List at offset 16, count at offset 24.
        Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block
        Let inst_count be proc get_block_instruction_count from MIR with block

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i

            Note: Uses: header operand slots + phi incomings (canonical enumerator)
            Let used_values be proc get_instruction_used_values from MirCFG with inst
            If used_values is not equal to 0:
                Let used_count be proc length from List with used_values
                Let op_idx be 0
                While op_idx is less than used_count:
                    Let value_id be proc get from List with used_values, op_idx
                    If value_id is not equal to 0:
                        If proc contains from Set with defined_in_block, value_id is equal to 0:
                            proc add from Set with uses, value_id
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set op_idx to op_idx plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Note: Uses: call/invoke argument Lists (prefix-embedded args@88),
            Note: which the header-slot enumerator does not cover.
            Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst
            If opcode is equal to 20304:
                Set inst to inst Note: direct CALL
                Let call_args be proc get_call_arguments from MIRNodes with inst
                If call_args is not equal to 0:
                    Let arg_count be proc get_call_argument_count from MIRNodes with inst
                    Let ai be 0
                    While ai is less than arg_count:
                        Let arg_value be proc get from List with call_args, ai
                        If arg_value is not equal to 0:
                            If proc contains from Set with defined_in_block, arg_value is equal to 0:
                                proc add from Set with uses, arg_value
                            End If
                        End If
                        Set ai to ai plus 1
                    End While
                End If
            Otherwise:
                If opcode is equal to 20305:
                    Note: CALL_INDIRECT — callee value-id is a use plus the args
                    Let indirect_callee be proc get_call_callee from MIRNodes with inst
                    If indirect_callee is not equal to 0:
                        If proc contains from Set with defined_in_block, indirect_callee is equal to 0:
                            proc add from Set with uses, indirect_callee
                        End If
                    End If
                    Let icall_args be proc get_call_arguments from MIRNodes with inst
                    If icall_args is not equal to 0:
                        Let iarg_count be proc get_call_argument_count from MIRNodes with inst
                        Let iai be 0
                        While iai is less than iarg_count:
                            Let iarg_value be proc get from List with icall_args, iai
                            If iarg_value is not equal to 0:
                                If proc contains from Set with defined_in_block, iarg_value is equal to 0:
                                    proc add from Set with uses, iarg_value
                                End If
                            End If
                            Set iai to iai plus 1
                        End While
                    End If
                End If
            End If

            Note: Definition: header value_id (offset 8); 0 = non-producing.
            Let result_value be proc get_mir_node_value_id from MIR with inst
            If result_value is not equal to 0:
                proc add from Set with defs, result_value
                proc add from Set with defined_in_block, result_value
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Note: Fixed-point iteration for live_in/live_out (backward)
    Let changed be 1
    Let iteration be 0
    Let value_id be 0
    Let j be 0

    While changed is equal to 1:
        If iteration is greater than or equal to 100:
            Set changed to 0
        Otherwise:
                Set changed to 0
                Set iteration to iteration plus 1

                Note: For each block (backward iteration, but order doesn't matter for correctness)
                Set b to 0
                While b is less than block_count:
                    Set block to proc get from List with blocks, b
                    Set block_id to proc get_mir_basic_block_id from MirCFG with block

                    Set liveness to proc omap_get from OrderedMap with liveness_infos, block_id
                    Let live_in be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 8
                    Let live_out be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 16
                    Set uses to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 40
                    Set defs to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 48

                    Note: Compute new live_out = ∪_{S ∈ succ[B]} live_in[S].
                    Note: Successors are a List of block IDS (canonical
                    Note: MIRBasicBlock offset 48); look up each successor's
                    Note: liveness by id through the ordered_map.
                    Let new_live_out be proc create from Set

                    Let successors be proc get_block_successors from MIR with block
                    Let succ_count be proc get_block_successor_count from MIR with block

                    Let s be 0
                    While s is less than succ_count:
                        Let succ_id be proc get from List with successors, s
                        Let succ_liveness be proc omap_get from OrderedMap with liveness_infos, succ_id
                        If succ_liveness is not equal to 0:
                            Let succ_live_in be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with succ_liveness, 8

                            Note: Union with successor's live_in
                            Let succ_live_in_list be proc to_list from Set with succ_live_in
                            Let succ_size be proc length from List with succ_live_in_list
                            Set j to 0
                            While j is less than succ_size:
                                Set value_id to proc get from List with succ_live_in_list, j
                                proc add from Set with new_live_out, value_id
                                Set j to j plus 1
                            End While
                        End If

                        Set s to s plus 1
                    End While

                    Note: Check if live_out changed
                    Let old_out_size be proc size from Set with live_out
                    Let new_out_size be proc size from Set with new_live_out
                    If old_out_size is not equal to new_out_size:
                        Set changed to 1
                    End If

                    Note: Update live_out
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with liveness, 16, new_live_out

                    Note: Compute live_in = uses ∪ (live_out - defs)
                    Let new_live_in be proc create from Set

                    Note: Add uses set
                    Let uses_list be proc to_list from Set with uses
                    Let uses_size be proc length from List with uses_list
                    Set j to 0
                    While j is less than uses_size:
                        Set value_id to proc get from List with uses_list, j
                        proc add from Set with new_live_in, value_id
                        Set j to j plus 1
                    End While

                    Note: Add (live_out - defs)
                    Let live_out_list be proc to_list from Set with new_live_out
                    Let live_out_size be proc length from List with live_out_list
                    Set j to 0
                    While j is less than live_out_size:
                        Set value_id to proc get from List with live_out_list, j
                        If proc contains from Set with defs, value_id is equal to 0:
                            proc add from Set with new_live_in, value_id
                        End If
                        Set j to j plus 1
                    End While

                    Note: Check if live_in changed
                    Let old_in_size be proc size from Set with live_in
                    Let new_in_size be proc size from Set with new_live_in
                    If old_in_size is not equal to new_in_size:
                        Set changed to 1
                    End If

                    Note: Update live_in
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with liveness, 8, new_live_in

                    Note: Update iteration count for debugging
                    Let iter_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 56
                    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with liveness, 56, iteration

                    Set b to b plus 1
                End While
        End If
    End While

    Note: Fixed-point reached or max iterations
    If iteration is greater than or equal to 100:
        Display "compute_live_variables_mir: max iterations reached"
    End If

    Return liveness_infos
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: DEF-USE CHAIN CONSTRUCTION (MIR SSA Form)
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Builds def-use chains for all SSA values in a MIR function.

In SSA form, each value has exactly one definition but potentially many uses.
The MIRValue structure already tracks use_list (offset 24), but this function
builds explicit DefUseChain structures for analysis passes.

Returns: Dictionary mapping value_id -> DefUseChain
@End Reasoning

Process called "build_def_use_chains_mir" that takes mir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_function is equal to 0:
        Display "build_def_use_chains_mir: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Canonical MIRFunction cfg slot is offset 8.
    Let mir_cfg be proc get_mir_function_cfg from MIR with mir_function
    If mir_cfg is equal to 0:
        Display "build_def_use_chains_mir: null CFG"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Canonical blocks List at MIRCFG offset 16.
    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from MirCFG with mir_cfg
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Return proc omap_create from OrderedMap
    End If
    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks

    Note: def-use chains keyed on the SSA value-id (integer key), so the
    Note: ordered_map is required (the string-hashing Dictionary segfaults
    Note: on integer keys). Pass 1 creates one chain per defined value.
    Let def_use_chains be proc omap_create from OrderedMap

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b
        Let block_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from MirCFG with block

        Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block
        Let inst_count be proc get_block_instruction_count from MIR with block

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i

            Note: Canonical: the SSA result value-id is the header value_id
            Note: (offset 8). 0 means the instruction produces no value.
            Let value_id be proc get_mir_node_value_id from MIR with inst
            If value_id is not equal to 0:
                Let chain be create_def_use_chain(value_id, block_id)
                proc omap_set from OrderedMap with def_use_chains, value_id, chain
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Note: Pass 2: for every instruction, enumerate the SSA value-ids it USES
    Note: (header operand slots + phi incomings via the canonical enumerator,
    Note: plus call/invoke argument Lists and the indirect callee) and append
    Note: the using instruction pointer and its block id to each used value's
    Note: chain. Post-OD-1, SSA use-lists are never materialized on MIRValue
    Note: records, so the chain is constructed by this forward scan rather
    Note: than by reading a use_list field.
    Set b to 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Set block to proc get from List with blocks, b
        Set block_id to proc get_mir_basic_block_id from MirCFG with block

        Let block_insts be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block
        Let block_inst_count be proc get_block_instruction_count from MIR with block

        Let k be 0
        While k is less than block_inst_count:
            Let use_inst be proc get from List with block_insts, k

            Note: Header-slot + phi uses through the canonical enumerator.
            Let used_values be proc get_instruction_used_values from MirCFG with use_inst
            If used_values is not equal to 0:
                Let used_count be proc length from List with used_values
                Let ui be 0
                While ui is less than used_count:
                    Let used_value be proc get from List with used_values, ui
                    If used_value is not equal to 0:
                        Let target_chain be proc omap_get from OrderedMap with def_use_chains, used_value
                        If target_chain is not equal to 0:
                            Let chain_use_ids be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with target_chain, 8
                            Let chain_use_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with target_chain, 24
                            proc append from List with chain_use_ids, use_inst
                            proc append from List with chain_use_blocks, block_id
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set ui to ui plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Note: Call/invoke argument-List uses (prefix-embedded args@88) and
            Note: the indirect callee value-id, which the header enumerator omits.
            Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with use_inst
            If opcode is equal to 20305:
                Let indirect_callee be proc get_call_callee from MIRNodes with use_inst
                If indirect_callee is not equal to 0:
                    Let callee_chain be proc omap_get from OrderedMap with def_use_chains, indirect_callee
                    If callee_chain is not equal to 0:
                        Let callee_use_ids be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_chain, 8
                        Let callee_use_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with callee_chain, 24
                        proc append from List with callee_use_ids, use_inst
                        proc append from List with callee_use_blocks, block_id
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            If opcode is equal to 20304 or opcode is equal to 20305:
                Let call_args be proc get_call_arguments from MIRNodes with use_inst
                If call_args is not equal to 0:
                    Let arg_count be proc get_call_argument_count from MIRNodes with use_inst
                    Let ai be 0
                    While ai is less than arg_count:
                        Let arg_value be proc get from List with call_args, ai
                        If arg_value is not equal to 0:
                            Let arg_chain be proc omap_get from OrderedMap with def_use_chains, arg_value
                            If arg_chain is not equal to 0:
                                Let arg_use_ids be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with arg_chain, 8
                                Let arg_use_blocks be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with arg_chain, 24
                                proc append from List with arg_use_ids, use_inst
                                proc append from List with arg_use_blocks, block_id
                            End If
                        End If
                        Set ai to ai plus 1
                    End While
                End If
            End If

            Set k to k plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return def_use_chains
End Process

@Reasoning
Builds use-def chains (reverse of def-use) for MIR.

For each use of a value, map back to its defining instruction.
In SSA form, this is trivial (each value has one def), but we maintain
the chain structure for consistency with non-SSA analysis.

Returns: Dictionary mapping use_id -> def_id
@End Reasoning

Process called "build_use_def_chains_mir" that takes mir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_function is equal to 0:
        Display "build_use_def_chains_mir: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Canonical MIRFunction cfg slot is offset 8.
    Let mir_cfg be proc get_mir_function_cfg from MIR with mir_function
    If mir_cfg is equal to 0:
        Display "build_use_def_chains_mir: null CFG"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Canonical blocks List at MIRCFG offset 16.
    Let blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from MirCFG with mir_cfg
    If blocks is equal to 0:
        Return proc omap_create from OrderedMap
    End If
    Let block_count be proc length from List with blocks

    Note: Maps each used SSA value-id to its defining instruction. In SSA
    Note: each value has exactly one definition, so the value-id is the
    Note: natural key — resolved through MIR.lookup_defining_instruction,
    Note: which consults the function's value_to_instruction registry. The
    Note: ordered_map keys on the integer value-id (the string-hashing
    Note: Dictionary segfaults on integer keys). Post-OD-1 there is no
    Note: MIRValue operand record carrying a def pointer; the canonical
    Note: enumerator yields value-id integers and the function registry is
    Note: the source of truth for definitions.
    Let use_def_chains be proc omap_create from OrderedMap

    Let b be 0
    While b is less than block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with blocks, b

        Let instructions be proc get_block_instructions from MIR with block
        Let inst_count be proc get_block_instruction_count from MIR with block

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than inst_count:
            Let inst be proc get from List with instructions, i

            Note: Header-slot + phi uses through the canonical enumerator.
            Let used_values be proc get_instruction_used_values from MirCFG with inst
            If used_values is not equal to 0:
                Let used_count be proc length from List with used_values
                Let ui be 0
                While ui is less than used_count:
                    Let value_id be proc get from List with used_values, ui
                    If value_id is not equal to 0:
                        If proc omap_contains from OrderedMap with use_def_chains, value_id is equal to 0:
                            Let def_inst be proc lookup_defining_instruction from MIR with mir_function, value_id
                            proc omap_set from OrderedMap with use_def_chains, value_id, def_inst
                        End If
                    End If
                    Set ui to ui plus 1
                End While
            End If

            Note: Call/invoke argument-List uses and the indirect callee.
            Let opcode be proc get_mir_node_opcode from MIR with inst
            If opcode is equal to 20305:
                Let indirect_callee be proc get_call_callee from MIRNodes with inst
                If indirect_callee is not equal to 0:
                    If proc omap_contains from OrderedMap with use_def_chains, indirect_callee is equal to 0:
                        Let callee_def be proc lookup_defining_instruction from MIR with mir_function, indirect_callee
                        proc omap_set from OrderedMap with use_def_chains, indirect_callee, callee_def
                    End If
                End If
            End If
            If opcode is equal to 20304 or opcode is equal to 20305:
                Let call_args be proc get_call_arguments from MIRNodes with inst
                If call_args is not equal to 0:
                    Let arg_count be proc get_call_argument_count from MIRNodes with inst
                    Let ai be 0
                    While ai is less than arg_count:
                        Let arg_value be proc get from List with call_args, ai
                        If arg_value is not equal to 0:
                            If proc omap_contains from OrderedMap with use_def_chains, arg_value is equal to 0:
                                Let arg_def be proc lookup_defining_instruction from MIR with mir_function, arg_value
                                proc omap_set from OrderedMap with use_def_chains, arg_value, arg_def
                            End If
                        End If
                        Set ai to ai plus 1
                    End While
                End If
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return use_def_chains
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: LIR REGISTER LIVENESS ANALYSIS
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Computes register liveness for an LIR function and populates the live_in
(offset 64) and live_out (offset 72) fields of every LIRBasicBlock.

The canonical, ABI-correct LIR liveness lives in
compiler/middle/gungnir/lir/liveness.runa (compute_function_liveness). That
module is the production register-allocation liveness owner: it resolves the
LIR instruction wrapper/base discriminator via lir_resolve_instruction_base
(block instruction Lists carry both bare LIRInstruction records and typed
wrappers — the opcode band 30000-30999 is the discriminator), models the
full System V ABI clobber/use sets at calls and syscalls, uses proper
register-sets, and emits the per-register live-range segments consumed by
the interference graph and the Briggs allocator. This data-flow-module entry
delegates to that single owner rather than maintaining a divergent,
wrapper-unaware copy: a second liveness implementation risks producing
results inconsistent with the allocator's view of the same function.

Returns: 1 if successful, 0 if error.
@End Reasoning

Process called "compute_lir_register_liveness" that takes lir_function as Integer returns Integer:
    If lir_function is equal to 0:
        Display "compute_lir_register_liveness: null function"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Delegate to the canonical LIR liveness owner. It populates each
    Note: LIRBasicBlock.live_in@64 / live_out@72 and computes the live-range
    Note: segments, returning 1 on success and 0 on any failure.
    Return proc compute_function_liveness from LIRLiveness with lir_function
End Process

Note: ============================================================================
Note: VERIFICATION AND DEBUGGING
Note: ============================================================================

@Reasoning
Verifies liveness analysis results for correctness.

Checks:
1. All values in live_out are either in defs or in live_in
2. All values in live_in are either in uses or in (live_out - defs)
3. No value is both defined and used before definition in same block

Returns: 1 if valid, 0 if errors found
@End Reasoning

Process called "verify_liveness" that takes liveness_infos as Integer returns Integer:
    If liveness_infos is equal to 0:
        Display "verify_liveness: null liveness_infos"
        Return 0
    End If

    Let errors be 0

    Note: Iterate the ordered_map of block_id -> LivenessInfo through the
    Note: entry cursor (omap_first / omap_entry_next).
    Let entry be proc omap_first from OrderedMap with liveness_infos
    While entry is not equal to 0:
        Let block_id be proc omap_entry_key from OrderedMap with entry
        Let liveness be proc omap_entry_value from OrderedMap with entry

        Let live_in be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 8
        Let live_out be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 16
        Let uses be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 40
        Let defs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 48

        Note: Verify: live_in = uses ∪ (live_out - defs)
        Let computed_live_in be proc create from Set

        Note: Add uses
        Let uses_list be proc to_list from Set with uses
        Let uses_size be proc length from List with uses_list
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than uses_size:
            Let value_id be proc get from List with uses_list, i
            proc add from Set with computed_live_in, value_id
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Note: Add (live_out - defs)
        Let live_out_list be proc to_list from Set with live_out
        Let live_out_size be proc length from List with live_out_list
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than live_out_size:
            Set value_id to proc get from List with live_out_list, i
            If proc contains from Set with defs, value_id is equal to 0:
                proc add from Set with computed_live_in, value_id
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While

        Note: Check if computed matches actual
        Let actual_size be proc size from Set with live_in
        Let computed_size be proc size from Set with computed_live_in

        If actual_size is not equal to computed_size:
            Let block_id_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with block_id
            Display proc string_concat from StringUtils with "verify_liveness: block ", block_id_str
            Display " live_in mismatch"
            Set errors to errors plus 1
        End If

        Set entry to proc omap_entry_next from OrderedMap with entry
    End While

    If errors is equal to 0:
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning
Prints liveness information for debugging.

Displays:
- Block ID
- Live-in set (values live on entry)
- Live-out set (values live on exit)
- Uses set (values used before definition)
- Defs set (values defined in block)
@End Reasoning

Process called "print_liveness_info" that takes liveness_infos as Integer returns Integer:
    If liveness_infos is equal to 0:
        Display "print_liveness_info: null liveness_infos"
        Return 0
    End If

    Display "=== Liveness Analysis Results ==="

    Note: Iterate the ordered_map of block_id -> LivenessInfo through the
    Note: entry cursor. Integer values are rendered through
    Note: StringUtils.integer_to_string because Display on a raw Integer
    Note: treats it as a string pointer (a crash).
    Let entry be proc omap_first from OrderedMap with liveness_infos
    While entry is not equal to 0:
        Let block_id be proc omap_entry_key from OrderedMap with entry
        Let liveness be proc omap_entry_value from OrderedMap with entry

        Let block_id_str be proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with block_id
        Display proc string_concat from StringUtils with "Block ", block_id_str
        Display ":"

        Let live_in be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 8
        Let live_out be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 16
        Let uses be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 40
        Let defs be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with liveness, 48

        Note: Print live_in
        Display "  live_in: {"
        Let live_in_list be proc to_list from Set with live_in
        Let live_in_size be proc length from List with live_in_list
        Let i be 0
        While i is less than live_in_size:
            Let value_id be proc get from List with live_in_list, i
            Display proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with value_id
            If i is less than (live_in_size minus 1):
                Display ", "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Display "}"

        Note: Print live_out
        Display "  live_out: {"
        Let live_out_list be proc to_list from Set with live_out
        Let live_out_size be proc length from List with live_out_list
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than live_out_size:
            Set value_id to proc get from List with live_out_list, i
            Display proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with value_id
            If i is less than (live_out_size minus 1):
                Display ", "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Display "}"

        Note: Print uses
        Display "  uses: {"
        Let uses_list be proc to_list from Set with uses
        Let uses_size be proc length from List with uses_list
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than uses_size:
            Set value_id to proc get from List with uses_list, i
            Display proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with value_id
            If i is less than (uses_size minus 1):
                Display ", "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Display "}"

        Note: Print defs
        Display "  defs: {"
        Let defs_list be proc to_list from Set with defs
        Let defs_size be proc length from List with defs_list
        Set i to 0
        While i is less than defs_size:
            Set value_id to proc get from List with defs_list, i
            Display proc integer_to_string from StringUtils with value_id
            If i is less than (defs_size minus 1):
                Display ", "
            End If
            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
        Display "}"

        Display ""
        Set entry to proc omap_entry_next from OrderedMap with entry
    End While

    Return 1
End Process

@Reasoning
Detects potentially uninitialized variables by checking if a variable is
used before being defined on all paths.

This is a safety analysis that can catch bugs early.

Algorithm:
1. For entry block, all uses that are not parameters are uninitialized
2. For other blocks, check if variable is in live_in but not in any
   predecessor's defs or parameters

Returns: List of (block_id, variable_id) tuples for uninitialized uses
@End Reasoning

Process called "detect_uninitialized_variables_mir" that takes mir_function as Integer, liveness_infos as Integer returns Integer:
    If mir_function is equal to 0 or liveness_infos is equal to 0:
        Display "detect_uninitialized_variables_mir: null inputs"
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Canonical MIRFunction cfg slot is offset 8.
    Let mir_cfg be proc get_mir_function_cfg from MIR with mir_function
    If mir_cfg is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Note: Get entry block and its canonical id.
    Let entry_block be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_cfg, 0
    Let entry_id be 0
    If entry_block is not equal to 0:
        Set entry_id to proc get_mir_basic_block_id from MirCFG with entry_block
    End If

    Note: Get parameters (these are initialized). Canonical MIRFunction
    Note: parameters List at offset 16, parameter_count at offset 24, holding
    Note: raw SSA value-ids.
    Let parameters be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_function, 16
    Let param_count be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with mir_function, 24

    Let param_set be proc create from Set
    Let p be 0
    While p is less than param_count:
        Let param_id be proc get from List with parameters, p
        proc add from Set with param_set, param_id
        Set p to p plus 1
    End While

    Note: List of uninitialized uses (block_id, value_id pairs)
    Let uninitialized be proc create from List

    Note: Check entry block uses
    Let entry_liveness be proc omap_get from OrderedMap with liveness_infos, entry_id
    If entry_liveness is not equal to 0:
        Let uses be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with entry_liveness, 40
        Let uses_list be proc to_list from Set with uses
        Let uses_size be proc length from List with uses_list

        Let i be 0
        While i is less than uses_size:
            Let value_id be proc get from List with uses_list, i

            Note: If not a parameter, it's uninitialized
            If proc contains from Set with param_set, value_id is equal to 0:
                Note: Create pair (block_id, value_id)
                Let pair be proc create from List
                proc append from List with pair, entry_id
                proc append from List with pair, value_id
                proc append from List with uninitialized, pair
            End If

            Set i to i plus 1
        End While
    End If

    Note: Check other blocks for uninitialized uses
    Note: Compute reaching definitions to see which defs reach each use
    Let reaching_defs be compute_reaching_definitions_mir(mir_cfg)
    If reaching_defs is equal to 0:
        Return uninitialized  Note: Return what we have (entry block only)
    End If

    Note: Canonical blocks List at MIRCFG offset 16.
    Let all_blocks be proc get_mir_cfg_blocks from MirCFG with mir_cfg
    If all_blocks is equal to 0:
        Return uninitialized
    End If
    Let all_block_count be proc length from List with all_blocks

    Note: For each block
    Let b be 0
    While b is less than all_block_count:
        Let block be proc get from List with all_blocks, b
        Let block_id be proc get_mir_basic_block_id from MirCFG with block

        Note: Skip entry block (already handled)
        If block_id is equal to entry_id:
            Set b to b plus 1
            Continue  Note: Already processed entry
        End If

        Note: Get reaching def info for this block
        Let reach_info be proc omap_get from OrderedMap with reaching_defs, block_id
        If reach_info is not equal to 0:
            Let reach_in be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with reach_info, 8

            Note: Get block liveness if available
            Let block_liveness be proc omap_get from OrderedMap with liveness_infos, block_id
            If block_liveness is not equal to 0:
                Set uses to proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with block_liveness, 40
                Set uses_list to proc to_list from Set with uses
                Set uses_size to proc length from List with uses_list

                Note: Check each use in this block
                Set i to 0
                While i is less than uses_size:
                    Set value_id to proc get from List with uses_list, i

                    Note: Check if this value has no reaching definition
                    Note: In SSA, if reach_in is empty for a value, it's uninitialized
                    Note: Check if value_id has a definition reaching this block
                    Let has_reaching_def be 0

                    Note: Search reach_in (a Set of defining INSTRUCTION
                    Note: pointers) for any def whose canonical result value_id
                    Note: (MIRNode header offset 8) equals value_id.
                    Let reach_in_list be proc to_list from Set with reach_in
                    Let reach_in_size be proc length from List with reach_in_list
                    Let j be 0
                    While j is less than reach_in_size:
                        Let def_inst be proc get from List with reach_in_list, j

                        Note: The defining instruction's SSA result value-id.
                        Let def_value_id be proc get_mir_node_value_id from MIR with def_inst
                        If def_value_id is not equal to 0:
                            If def_value_id is equal to value_id:
                                Set has_reaching_def to 1
                            End If
                        End If

                        Set j to j plus 1
                    End While

                    Note: If not a parameter and no reaching def, it's uninitialized
                    If has_reaching_def is equal to 0 and proc contains from Set with param_set, value_id is equal to 0:
                        Set pair to proc create from List
                        proc append from List with pair, block_id
                        proc append from List with pair, value_id
                        proc append from List with uninitialized, pair
                    End If

                    Set i to i plus 1
                End While
            End If
        End If

        Set b to b plus 1
    End While

    Return uninitialized
End Process
